<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA VOICES / A FORUM FOR COMMUNITY ISSUES: SECOND OPINION / 
OTHER MEDIA; INDIA JOURNAL; WILSON IGNORES WORK ETHIC OF ILLEGAL IMMIGRANTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From a column by Nimmi Raghunathan in India Journal, a weekly published in 
Emeryville, Ca., and distributed statewide. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Take a walk on Pioneer Boulevard. Look at the salespeople, the waiters, the 
cooks. What do you see? People working hard, long hours at minimum wages, 
trying to make those greenbacks which will allow them to pay their taxes, their 
rent and high school tuition. They are not on welfare, have no insurance, no 
car in a city that has practically no public transport worth its name, and they 
owe their very survival to their employer. 
</P>
<P>
 But these conditions seem less terrible than what they had to put up with back 
home, in India. In America, it's easier to get a job that pays. Even better, 
American does not dim the stars in the eyes they come with when they get across 
the border -- several even go on to own their own small businesses. Their 
children learn English, understand the value of hard work and money early 
enough to pick up jobs at the McDonald's and the Thriftys so they can put 
themselves through school. 
</P>
<P>
 Gov. Pete Wilson doesn't see it this way. He can't afford to. He is running 
for office again. And when times are tough, California politicians find 
immigrant-bashing the easiest way of getting and diverting attention. They have 
done it to the Chinese, the Japanese and now it's the Mexicans and Asians. 
</P>
<P>
 The answer to the state's social and economic woes, as Wilson sees it, is 
immigration. He doesn't believe that immigrants come here for economic 
betterment. They come here, he claims, for social services. He doesn't care to 
look at studies that show new entrants don't like to be on welfare and average 
lower levels of welfare than citizens. He obviously does not know that within 
three to five years their earnings surpass the average American household and 
they begin to pay taxes. 
</P>
<P>
 So, he has embraced SOS -- the oxymoron acronym for the xenophobic Save Our 
State initiative which, anyway you look at it, is a legal and moral mire. 
Purportedly, the initiative, which will be voted on in November, seeks to stem 
illegal immigration to California. 
</P>
<P>
 While no one can condone illegal immigration, the means used are questionable. 
The central idea of this is to deny and expel any child from school who does 
not have documents to prove his or her legal status. And if the school finds 
out that either of the parents is undocumented, they will hear from the INS. 
Schools in the future will do more than educate -- they will be the 
authorities' unofficial spooks. Remind you of the Stalin era? 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Opinion 
