<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOUTHLAND PREVIEW / THE BUSINESS WEEK AHEAD: SAN DIEGO COUNTY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Auto Safety Hearing: The U.S. Dept. of Transportation will hold a town meeting 
in San Diego on Thursday on proposals to to require car makers to give 
consumers additional safety information on tires, crash worthiness, child 
safety, roll-over propensity and other areas.Roll-over propensity is a topic of 
much interest to some consumer groups and insurers who want car makers to 
adhere to stricter road stability standards. More than 9,000 passengers are 
killed annually as a result of vehicle roll-overs, a third of all vehicle 
occupant deaths. Nine out of 10 roll-over accidents involve a single vehicle. 
The meeting is one of four that the DOT's National Highway Traffic Safety 
Administration is conducting nationwide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
