</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Canadians Cut Back on Cross-Border Shopping: Canadians are making fewer day 
trips to the United States, indicating that cross-border shopping may be 
falling sharply.Canadian residents took 3 million day trips across the border 
in June, the smallest number since June, 1988, the government statistical 
agency reported. That was down 1.4% from May. Cross-border shopping accelerated 
during the recession but has been steadily dropping since early 1992. Analysts 
say that reflects the U.S. dollar's nearly 15% rise in value against the 
Canadian dollar in the past 2 1/2 years, making U.S.-bought goods more 
expensive for Canadians. 
</P>
